  <h2>Investment Risks & Factors</h2>

  <h3>Upside Potential</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Data Consumption Growth:</strong> Continued exponential growth in mobile data and 5G deployment worldwide driving tenant leasing and amendments.</li>
    <li><strong>Edge Computing:</strong> Potential to monetize real estate footprint at tower bases for micro-data centers and edge computing infrastructure.</li>
    <li><strong>International Expansion:</strong> Growth in emerging markets where mobile penetration and network infrastructure are still maturing.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Exposure:</strong> As a heavily indebted REIT ($45B in debt), higher sustained interest rates increase borrowing costs and often reduce the valuation multiples the market is willing to pay.</li>
    <li><strong>Carrier Consolidation:</strong> Mergers among telecom operators (like the historical Sprint/T-Mobile merger) can lead to redundant tower overlap and increased churn.</li>
    <li><strong>Technology Shifts:</strong> Alternative technologies like low-earth orbit (LEO) satellite networks (e.g., Starlink) could potentially compete with terrestrial cellular networks in certain regions.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is American Tower's intrinsic value negative in some scenarios?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">American Tower carries a substantial amount of debt (around $45 billion). If the discount rate is high and growth assumptions are low, the present value of future cash flows (Enterprise Value) may not be large enough to offset this massive debt burden, resulting in a theoretical negative Equity Value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use Free Cash Flow instead of AFFO?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">For REITs, Adjusted Funds From Operations (AFFO) is typically the standard metric. However, Free Cash Flow (Operating Cash Flow minus Capital Expenditures) is fundamentally similar and serves as a highly robust input for a traditional DCF model to measure cash available to all stakeholders.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the dividend factor into this valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A DCF inherently captures the value of dividends by discounting the free cash flow that *supports* those dividends. If we assume the cash flow belongs to the shareholder, we don't need to value the dividend separately.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

